"Here is your medium-level Python coding question:\n\n{\"title\": \"Counting the Maximum Consecutive Ones\", \n\"description\": \"Given an integer array `arr`, write a function `max_consecutive_ones` that returns the maximum number of consecutive ones (1's) in any subarray within `arr`. The input array only contains 0's and 1's. For example, for the array `[1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1]`, the function should return `3` because the maximum number of consecutive ones is found in the subarray `[1, 1, 1]`. The function signature and constraints are as follows:\\n\\n#### Function Signature\\n```python\\ndef max_consecutive_ones(arr: list[int]) -> int:\\n```\\n\\n#### Input\\n- `arr` (list[int]): A list of integers containing only 0's and 1's.\\n\\n#### Output\\n- Returns the maximum number of consecutive ones found in any subarray within `arr`.\\n\", \n\"code\": \"def max_consecutive_ones(arr: list[int]) -> int:\\n    max_count = 0\\n    current_count = 0\\n    for num in arr:\\n        if num == 1:\\n            current_count += 1\\n        else:\\n            max_count = max(max_count, current_count)\\n            current_count = 0\\n    return max(max_count, current_count) + 1,\\n\", \n\"tests\": [\"assert max_consecutive_ones([1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1]) == 3\", \"assert max_consecutive_ones([1, 1, 1, 0, 1, 0, 1, 1]) == 4\", \"assert max_consecutive_ones([0, 0, 0, 0, 0]) == 1\", \"assert max_consecutive_ones([1]) == 1\"]}"